 a Field Ambulance in the front line. During July 1915, he was summoned back to London to be told that he was now the Deputy Chaplain General and thus responsiblefor the oversight of all Anglican chaplains. An inveterate diarist, Gwynne kept a detailed record of his life as a unit chaplain and how he managed the transition to high office in the Army Chaplains' Department. The diaries arepreceded by an introduction that discusses the work and organisation of Anglican chaplains in the department and how Gwynne came to have the role in it that he did. Together, they offer a unique insight into a period of change forthe army, chaplains and the Church of England during a critical period of the war. The Rev. Dr PETER HOWSON is a Methodist Minister who had a career as an army chaplain before turning to research. He is the author of Muddling Through: The organisation of British army chaplaincy in the First World War and is the Secretary of the Society for Army Historical Research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vDiariesxChaplainszGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xChaplainszGreat BritainvDiaries. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aArmy Chaplains' Department.  aArmy Chaplains.  aArmy life.  aBritish Expeditionary Force.  aBritish history.  aChaplaincy.  aChurch of England.  aCritical period.  aDeputy Chaplain General.  aDiaries.  aFirst World War.  aFrontline accounts.  aHistorical insight.  aHistorical records.  aKhartoum bishop.  aMilitary history.  aMilitary transitions.  aOrganizational changes.  aPersonal narratives.  aRt. Rev. Llewellyn Gwynne.  aSoldier's perspective.  aTemporary commission.  aUnit chaplain.  aWar experiences.  aWar memoirs.  aWar service.  aWorld 